body:
> actually if YUL is supported by solc then it is already implemented

It is implemented, but it isn't user friendly. Lets say I want to check `sstore(1,1)`. I need to put this code in the `solidity:` section:

```

  solidity: |
      contract Yul {
        function val2Storage() public
        {
          assembly {
            sstore(1,1)
          }
        }   // function val2Storage
      }     // contract Yul
```

Four lines of prefix and three lines of postfix to be able to use Yul. If we want to encourage people to use it, it needs to be easy. For example, imagine this structure:

```
    cccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccccc:
      balance: '0x0ba1a9ce0ba1a9ce'
      code: |            
        yul(uint256 a, uint256 b) {
           sstore(a, b)
        }
      nonce: '0'
      storage: {}
```

Then retesteth can add all the necessary syntax to create the actual Solidity code, with the address in the contract name:
```
  solidity: |
      contract addr_ccc...ccc {
        function yul(uint256 a, uint256 b) public
        {
          assembly {
            sstore(a, b)
          }
        }   // function yul
      }     // contract addr_ccc...ccc
```

The contract name is irrelevant, because we connect it to the address in retesteth. The name of the function and its parameters are specified by the test author, so they'll know to use `data: :abi yul(uint256,uint256) 5 6` in the transaction.

You can use `solc --assemble <file.yul>` where `file.yul` is a simple block (can also use functions):
```
{
  function f(a, b) -> c {
    c := add(a, b)
  }

  mstore(0, f(1, 2))
  return(0, 32)
}
```
